<h2>Events in April 2019</h2>
<br><br>
<strong>Heavy precipitation in the Mediterranean region</strong>
<br><br>
In the week of 23 April a series of active low pressure areas and corresponding frontal systems moved into the westen and central Mediterranean. It produced heavy convective and orographic rainfall along the southern Alpine flank in north Italy and northwest Slovenia, pushing precipitation into southern Switzerland as well. Totals in excess of 100 mm / 48h, locally over 200 mm / 48h occured.
<br><br>
Higher elevations in this zone had seen 20-40 cm of snow, and locally 50 cm in some places.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/apr2019/AL2300large.png"><img alt="" src="../images/apr2019/AL2300large.png" width="500px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1 Weathermap of 23 April 2019 00Z(Source:KNMI )</em>
<br><br>
Over SE Spain persistent convective and orographic rainfall resulted in totals of 50-100 mm over a wide region and locally up to 250-350 mm.
<br><br>
<br><br>
<a href="../images/apr2019/Satellite_23_April_12Z.png"><img alt="" src="../images/apr2019/Satellite_23_April_12Z.png" width="500px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2 Visible satellite image of 23 April 2019 12Z(Source:NASA )</em>
<br><br>
<strong>Large tornado in Romania</strong>
<br><br>
In the last days of April very unstable conditions occurred over part of SE-Europe due to the inflow of moist and warm air from the south. Along a cold front over Romania an outbreaks of heavy thunderstorms developed with even a large tornado which was covered in the media in many countries.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/apr2019/Tornado_Romania.jpg"><img alt="" src="../images/apr2019/Tornado_Romania.jpg" width="400px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 3 Photograph of Enormous Tornado in Calarasi, Romania of 30 April 2019 (Source: watchers.news)</em>
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for April 2019</h2>
<br><br>
In Northwest Europe the number of warm days was, particularly during day-times, higher than in the reference period 1981-2010 (Figure 4). As 'warm' relates to the highest 10 percentile range, the reference number of warm days per month is about 3. In Iceland and parts of Scandinavia about 50% of the days were warm days.
<br><br>
